3. WLAN (Wireless Local Area Network)
Definition
A LAN that uses wireless communication instead of physical cables.
Technologies
Wi-Fi (IEEE 802.11)
Frequency Bands
2.4 GHz
Pros:
Longer range
Cons:
More interference
5 GHz
Pros:
Faster speed
Cons:
Shorter range
6 GHz (Wi-Fi 6E)
Pros:
Less congestion
Higher speed
Examples
Home Wi-Fi
Airport Wi-Fi
College Wi-Fi
4. CAN (Campus Area Network)
Definition
Connects multiple LANs within a campus or institution.
Coverage
1–5 km
Examples
University campus
Research centers
Corporate campuses
Components
Fiber optic backbone
Core switches
Routers
Advantages
Centralized management
High-speed communication
5. MAN (Metropolitan Area Network)
Definition
A network spanning an entire city or metropolitan area.
Coverage
5–50 km
Technologies
Fiber Optics
Microwave Links
Examples
City-wide government network
Cable TV network
Advantages
Connects multiple LANs
Disadvantages
Expensive infrastructure
6. WAN (Wide Area Network)
Definition
A network covering large geographical areas such as states, countries, or continents.
Coverage
100 km to thousands of kilometers.
Technologies
Leased lines
MPLS
Satellite
Fiber Optics
Examples
Banking network
Railway network
Corporate multinational network
Advantages
Global communication
Disadvantages
Higher latency
Expensive management
